title: For Sale:  High Standard 10-X / 10X / 10x SH series. Serious inquiries only
postcontent:
If you're reading this, you were just curious why it's listed for as much as it is, OR, you're a marksman. What I have is a championship winning High Standard 10-X model 9372 custom target pistol built between 1981 and 1982. If you're familiar with this pistol, you know that there wasn't a single 10-X sold that wasn't capable of a 5 shot group with less than 0.310" spread. This one is no different and has won the Colorado State Silhouette Championship. I'm well aware how rare it is to come across this weapon and moreso aware of what the last one that landed on an auction site went for so talking to me about blue book "value" isn't relevant in any form and won't be replied to. This is possibly one of the rarest 10-X's available as the gunsmith double stamped his initials. I've been trying to find out if he can be contacted to find out if this was the case with many, or just a handful, but either way, the only other 10-X I've found is lightyears away in condition. My 10-X has Box, Tool, 3 magazines and has been meticulously maintained. The one on the auction site has visible signs of degradation, no box, and the one magazine has the initials carved into it. The last one that came available in similar condition as mine was sold for ~$5600. I don't expect to get that but I also don't want to see a bunch of emails asking if I'd take $1500

I didn't realize the limit on photos existed prior to submitting so feel free to contact me for more detailed photos.

postcontent:
Hi all.  I purchased 4000 of these projectiles planning to reload in this caliber, but I have sold all of my 40 S&W caliber pistols so I no longer need these heavy boxes hanging around in the house.  I purchased them directly from Midway USA I paid $542.95 with shipping.  I am asking for $140 per 1000.  If you buy all 4000 in one shot then I will drop the price to $500 which is a couple bucks under the per 1000 price I paid and I am eating the shipping fees. 

Description straight from MidwayUSA website:

Rainier LeadSafe Bullets 40 S&W, 10mm Auto (400 Diameter) 180 Grain Plated Hollow Point

Rainier offers a large selection of swaged lead core copper plated bullets that are low in cost but substantially high in accuracy. Rainier swages their bullets twice with lead wire in an effort to ensure the tightest uniformity as well as prevention of premature wearing of barrels. While Rainier doesn't publish their own reloading information, they recommended using lead bullet load data when loading their bullets as well as a slight taper crimp. Rainier recommends a maximum velocity of 1,500 fps. 

These bullets feature a lead core that is completely covered by copper plating. They are resized after being plated with approximately 0.004" of copper plating. This unique design makes them suitable for most indoor ranges, which often require the use of bullets with no exposed lead. The base is slightly concave to maximize the bullet to bore seal.

Although retaining some features of the old rifle, the SUB-2000 is a completely new design. Emphasis has been put on consumer safety, but without impeding the performance. Polymers are used to a large extent, resulting in increased durability and reduced price. The SUB-2000 is available in 9 mm Luger or .40 S&W calibers.

The bolt can be locked in the rear position by the operating handle. The main safety is of protected push bolt type disconnecting the trigger bar and interlocking the hammer and sear. By rotating the barrel upwards and back, the SUB-2000 can be reduced to a size of 16" x 7" to facilitate secure storage and utilize the internal deployment lock which is operated by a proprietary key. The rear sight is of aperture type and the fluorescent front sight can be adjusted for windage and elevation. The SUB-2000 can easily be disassembled for cleaning or inspection without tools.

The 9mm SUB-2000 can be configured in the following magazine types: GLK17, GLK19, S&W59, BERETTA92,  SIG226.

The Beltminus Patrol Kit uses Blue Force Gear's MOLLEminus system, an extremely light weight and durable MOLLE system that is still 100% backwards compatible with traditional MOLLE/PALS systems, and is equal to or stronger than 1000D Cordura while being up to 60% lighter.

title: For Sale:  Glock 19 gen 4 nearly new
postcontent:
I bought it new last year. Put around 200 rounds through; never a hiccup. I LOVE IT!  Problem is I'm very small framed and it's too bulky for me for conceled carry and I can't afford to just buy another gun. 
As far as mods go, three things: 
1. I put a "SiderLock" trigger on it. Basically same pull as factory with the exception of having an integrated safety, and all metal construction. From all my research it's a better trigger. 
2. I personally rounded the trigger guard. It is a clean job, though no stippling done. I'm a finish carpenter and took my time with it so it looks good. It's actually hard to tell unless you look for it. 
3. I put a glue-on clip on it for those times I've carried iwb without a holster (rarely). 
I don't use the safety much.  I put the saftey on there so I'd have the option. I did my research on it and reviews are great. There's very little chance of engaging it inadvertently and it's a nice option to have.  I've found it especially useful when teaching someone to shoot and basic safety rules like finger off the trigger. It just gives me that added security that they don't make a rookie mistake. And they can and do. Ask me how I know lol!
It comes with the box and paperwork, including the blackstrap attachments for the grip, and four standard, 15rd mags. 
No ammo. 
I am a licensed Georgia ccp holder and resident. 

Text me with any questions.
